{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514785"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:26:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:26:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12374"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12374"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.03,0.02,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56385"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4888"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41936"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"3338"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46325"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56385"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a persistent dry, non-productive cough that is worse at night. He has no other symptoms, particularly no pleuritic chest pain or shortness of breath. His medical history includes hypertension, childhood asthma and occasional episodes of heartburn. His medications include amlodipine and perindopril (which he commenced three months ago to improve hypertensive control). He does not smoke and drinks about three glasses of wine at weekends. His daughter has a pet cat. He works as an architect and his occupation often involves him spending hours at construction sites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 128/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Cardiac examination is unremarkable. On chest auscultation, there are clear bilateral breath sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perindopril-induced cough","Asthma exacerbation","Animal-related allergy","Occupational-related asthma","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most probable cause for this patient\u0027s symptoms is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eperindopril-induced cough\u003C/strong\u003E. ACE inhibitors, such as perindopril, are well-known to cause a persistent dry cough as a side effect. This cough can occur immediately after starting the medication or develop several months later, as in this case. The cough is typically dry, non-productive, and often worse at night, matching the patient\u0027s presentation. The symptom typically resolves when the ACE inhibitor is replaced by an angiotensin II receptor blocker (ARB).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Easthma exacerbation\u003C/strong\u003E might result in a cough, but it would likely be accompanied by other symptoms like increased wheezing, chest tightness, and shortness of breath, especially after physical exertion. The patient\u0027s clear lung fields on examination and the history of childhood asthma that is likely well-controlled at his current age suggest that an asthma exacerbation is unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eanimal-related allergy\u003C/strong\u003E due to household pets could induce a cough. However, such allergies often manifest with other symptoms like sneezing, nasal congestion, or itchy eyes. There is no mention of these symptoms in the patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccupational-related asthma\u003C/strong\u003E is plausible given the patient\u0027s occupation in the construction industry where exposure to various irritants is common. However, occupational asthma usually comes with other symptoms like shortness of breath and wheezing that improve away from the workplace. In this patient, the cough is not described as having such variability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present with chronic cough, especially when lying down at night. However, the absence of persistent classic reflux symptoms, e.g. heartburn, regurgitation and abdominal/chest pain, diminishes the likelihood of this being the primary cause of the cough.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A persistent dry cough can be a common side effect of ACE inhibitors, typically occurring within weeks to months of starting the medication.","When evaluating a patient on ACE inhibitors with a new-onset cough, consider the medication as a potential cause before pursuing other diagnoses.","ACE inhibitor-induced cough is typically dry, non-productive, and often worse at night."],"references":["Pinto B, Jadhav U, Singhai P, Sadhanandham S, Shah N. ACEI-induced cough: A review of current evidence and its practical implications for optimal CV risk reduction. Indian Heart J. 2020 Sep-Oct;72(5):345-350. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7670268/","Olvera Lopez E, Parmar M, Pendela VS, et al. Lisinopril. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 Jul 12. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482230/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41936"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12374"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41936"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-20T12:48:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-20T20:26:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4888"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56385"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the e